post_text:
To all of our bookworms: our D65 Librarians want you to continue reading! Here's their friendly reminder to invest in your love of books with a library card. Register for your Evanston library card at epl.org or your Skokie one at Skokielibrary.info. When in doubt, feel free to connect with your school's librarian for more help and info.

Fun fact: Did you know that both Evanston and Skokie libraries have curbside pickup available? What are you waiting for?! Use your library card and grab your favorite Lemony Snicket book now!

post_text: Don‚Äôt let our students go uncounted - complete the information for the 2020 Census today! Responding to the census allows our school district and your student to receive fair funding for things such as school supplies, teachers, and school lunches. The deadline to submit information for the 2020 Census is now Wednesday, September 30th. You can complete your census application online at https://my2020census.gov/ or via phone call at 844-330-2020 (English); 844-468-2020 (Spanish).

post_text: Earlier this month, we congratulated Olivia Ohlson, 8th grader at Haven Middle School, for being awarded the Daily Point of Light Award from former President, George H.W. Bush's Points of Light Foundation for her volunteer service in the D65 community. Well, we have even better news! In addition to this award, Olivia has also been nominated for the foundation's Inspiration Honor Roll for her hard work. Olivia‚Äôs story has the chance to be chosen as one of the Top Ten Inspiration Spotlight Stories that will be highlighted during the foundation's Awards Celebration livestream experience on September 26. Keep up the great work, Olivia!

post_text:
DISTRICT 65 LEARNING PATHWAYS - As part of our return guidance shared on July 22, all students will participate in remote learning from August 27-September 28. By July 31, all families must select (via the SISK12 Parent Portal) if their child will continue in remote learning or begin in-person learning (if it is safe to do so).* Learn more: bit.ly/32JatYE #AllInD65 #D65ReturntoLearn

*In-Person Learning will be held on Tuesdays-Fridays/Mondays Remote Learning; if there are more families who select in-person learning than our buildings can safely accommodate, it may be necessary to implement alternate student attendance schedules.

post_text: Our 6th graders at Nichols did an incredible job with the Britto Art Challenge this week! Romero Britto is a Brazilian artist, painter, serigrapher and sculptor. D65 family - have a great holiday weekend!

post_text: While we may have all expected news that our schools would remain closed through the end of the school year, we are still saddened and disappointed. We miss our students and our staff! FAMILY SHARING CIRCLES - Start by using the same 5 Circle norms that children use in school:

We sit in a Circle with all included
We use and respect a talking piece
We speak and listen from the heart
We use ‚ÄúI-Statements‚Äù: ‚ÄúI think‚Äù, ‚ÄúI feel‚Äù, ‚ÄúI believe‚Äù
What is said in Circle, stays in Circle

Talk About:
1. How do you use what you are good at to help others?
2. What makes you feel safe?

Sunday, January 19 - Attend the ‚ÄúDr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Day of Celebration and Evanston Unity" at the newly renovated Fleetwood-Jourdain Community Center. This community celebration promises to be inspiring and entertaining, as it will honor Dr. King's legacy through musical performances and speeches.

More ways to celebrate: Enjoy drop-in crafts and film screenings at the Evanston Public Library, Northwestern University's candlelight vigil, and more. (Source: City of Evanston)

FYI - This afternoon, Lincoln Elementary was under a brief soft lockdown as a result of an incident that occurred during recess. While on the playground, a verbal threat was made by a couple of teenagers and directed towards several of our students. All students and staff are safe.

We contacted the Evanston Police Department who located and interviewed the teenagers who were involved in the incident. They have assured us that there is no credible threat to students or the school and that it is safe to dismiss students at the normal time this afternoon. Please be advised that there will be School Resource Officers at the school during dismissal.

Lincoln Community - Please be advised that there was a police incident about a block away from Lincoln around the time of student arrival this morning. As a precaution, staff brought all students inside.

The Evanston Police Department handled the situation and the person involved in the incident is currently in custody. This incident involved a theft and was a non-school related matter. All students and staff are safe. Please be advised that there was a strong police presence outside of the school. Lincoln social workers are on-hand if any students have questions or need support.

We appreciate the quick response of our staff and the Evanston Police Department.

post_text: Kingsley elementary is seeking a principal who will value, support, and champion the district‚Äôs commitment to equity. This includes a commitment to addressing the academic achievement gap. The principal should have a deep understanding of high quality instruction that includes culturally relevant teaching and must be able to foster a positive and nurturing learning environment for all students. He/she/they must evaluate and support teachers, providing meaningful feedback, as well as opportunities for professional growth and leadership. Finally, the new leader must keep what is best for students at the forefront of all decision making. Please apply online at www.district65.net.

post_text: Chute Middle School is transforming into the Land of Oz for the 2019 musical! Over 230 6th-8th grade students, staff members, and volunteers have worked for months to bring the classic production to life. Held every three years, our talented Chute students are piecing the all-school production together from start to finish, from costume and set design to acting, singing, and dancing, from the orchestra to advertising - students are doing it all with the help of Chute educators! Don't miss it! bit.ly/2TtP6Hn

While it's not always easy to keep up with Mother Nature, our team did their best to ensure school grounds were ready, accessible, and safe for all. Thank you to our district-wide B&G Team! (Pictured: Willard Team)

post_text: District 65 is seeking a Principal with a passion for being in an elementary school setting to become the next principal of Dawes Elementary School. We are also looking for a candidate who will bring stability to a community that has experienced recent leadership changes. Dawes is a unique and diverse elementary school serving students K-5 with multiple programs including: general education, Two-Way Immersion (TWI), English Language Learners (ELL), and a continuum of special education services. Dawes‚Äô new leader must be able to establish and promote high expectations for all learners, as well as collaborate with a variety of stakeholders to explore, understand and celebrate the diversity that makes Dawes such a special school community. If you are committed to the success of all children, professional growth for all teachers, and parent engagement, please complete our online application at www.district65.net!
text:
District 65 is seeking a Principal with a passion for being in an elementary school setting to become the next principal of Dawes Elementary School. We are also looking for a candidate who will bring stability to a community that has experienced recent leadership changes. Dawes is a unique and diverse elementary school serving students K-5 with multiple programs including: general education, Two-Way Immersion (TWI), English Language Learners (ELL), and a continuum of special education services. Dawes‚Äô new leader must be able to establish and promote high expectations for all learners, as well as collaborate with a variety of stakeholders to explore, understand and celebrate the diversity that makes Dawes such a special school community. If you are committed to the success of all children, professional growth for all teachers, and parent engagement, please complete our online application at www.district65.net!

post_text: Over 70 7th and 8th grade students from Haven Middle School collaborated on their school's fall play - Know Me. The original piece was inspired by two big ideas, ‚ÄúYou don't know me until you know my story" and "I have the right to be myself." The play examined issues that the students identified as important to them and their experiences and included body image, gender stereotypes, LGBTQAI rights, race, and loneliness. Bravo to all of our students for sharing their truth through the original scenes, songs, poems, and artwork!
